I
hromatin consists of nucleosomes bound to  in patterns correlated with  primary sequence (1β€“4). urrent β€�nucleosome sequencingβ€™ experiments indicate a great deal of heterogeneity of nucleosome positioning, with some regions of precise nucleosome occupancy and other regions that are apparently much less well ordered. he origin of nucleosome β€�positioningβ€™ along  remains controversial: some researchers stress the role of the -sequence-dependence of histoneβ€“ interactions (1β€“3), whereas others emphasize roles of other mechanisms to control positions of nucleosomes, notably β€�statisticalβ€™ positioning of nucleosomes (5β€“8).
tatistical positioning follows from the existence of β€�barriersβ€™ to nucleosome formation, i.e. locations along  that nucleosomes are unable to occupy. or example, non-histone proteins bound strongly to a specific  site might sterically prevent nucleosomes from occupying that location. he correlations in nucleosome positions near such a barrier can generate spatial variations of nucleosome occupancy, but without the necessity of any intrinsic -sequence-dependence of histoneβ€“ interactions (5). tatistical positioning near barriers has been suggested as the origin of nucleosome positioning patterns near transcription start sites () (6,7,9β€“11), but without mechanistic understanding of the origin of the barriers. owever, all theoretical analyses of statistical positioning have been based on β€�thermalβ€™ equilibration of nucleosome positions along  (12β€“14).
he rates at which nucleosomes can become positioned are crucially dependent on the kinetics of nucleosome placement, relocation and eviction. iven the  free energy associated with histoneβ€“ interactions in a nucleosome (15,16), eviction requires non-thermal processes. fficient nucleosome relocation (β€�slidingβ€™) also requires non-thermal kinetics due to the very slow thermal diffusion of nucleosomes along  (17β€“19). his casts considerable doubt on the relevance of equilibrium-statistical-mechanical descriptions of nucleosome positioning (20). ndeed, prior work has shown that assembly of chromatin with nucleosomes spaced by  bp linker s on biologically relevant timescales requires active (non-thermal, e.g. -powered) chromatin remodeling. n the absence of active remodeling, nucleosomes cannot reach the degree of packing and positioning observed in vivo (17).
n accord with this, hang et al. (7) have observed experimentally that the apparent statistical positioning observed near  barriers requires , presumably to facilitate chromatin remodeling. owever, at the same time, other experiments suggest that  sequence does play a role in positioning nucleosomes near  (1,10,21). hese observations suggest that the organization of nucleosomes near  is determined by interplay between primary  sequence-dependent nucleosome positioning and statistical positioning near nucleosome barriers, but driven by non-thermal -dependent chromatin remodeling dynamics outside of the realm of description in terms of free energies and the (thermal equilibrium) oltzmann distribution.
rior theoretical studies on nucleosome positioning near s suggest that  sequence is not a crucial factor in reproducing experimentally observed nucleosome occupancy (5,13). owever, a number of recent experiments indicate that sequence-dependent nucleosome stability near s has an important role in a range of biological functions (21β€“23). his leads to an apparent paradox: sequence appears to influence nucleosome stability and biological function, but not occupancy.
e can anticipate that, owing to -driven remodeling, nucleosome organization is highly dynamic, with kinetics and time-averaged properties which are far from thermodynamic equilibrium. hese non-thermal nucleosome dynamics likely control site accessibility of  binding sites for site-specific -binding proteins, perhaps most notably near s. iven our previously developed model for chromatin dynamics with sequence-dependent nucleosomeβ€“ interactions and -dependent remodeling (17), we decided to analyze what the dynamics of nucleosomes would be near to nucleosome-depleted barriers.
ere we develop a theoretical description of nucleosome dynamics near barriers where we can examine the effect of sequence as well as -dependent remodeling. e find that establishment of apparent statistical positioning on biologically relevant timescales requires active chromatin remodeling; statistical positioning cannot occur by the action of thermal fluctuations alone, in accord with the result of hang et al. (7). urthermore, we find that  sequence does control nucleosome occupancy relatively near to  barriers, but that this effect is suppressed when one averages occupancy over many genes. omputing nucleosome assembly kinetics, we show that the timescale for formation of statistical positioning is proportional to the timescale of active nucleosome disassembly. inally, we also observe that the kinetics of site exposure show strong sequence dependence adjacent to nucleosome barriers, indicating that there may be strong effects of -sequence-dependent nucleosome binding on, for example, the kinetics of gene regulation.
he calculations of this article are all applied to chromatin dynamics of accharomyces cerevisiae, for which detailed genome-wide nucleosome positioning and remodeling enzyme kinetic data exist. owever, owing to the generic nature of our model, we anticipate that our results should be at least qualitatively relevant to chromatin dynamics across a wide range of eukaryote species.
odel. In our model, we take into account four major factors that influence nucleosome assembly: DNAβ€“histone interactions, nucleosomeβ€“nucleosome interactions, ATP-dependent nucleosome reorganization and the effect of barriers near TSSs. DNA, which is considered as a linear lattice of N base pairs, interacts with histone octamers in a sequence-dependent manner. In the model, each nucleosome is treated as a particle that occupies k = 147 bp of DNA. A nucleosome starting at  bp on DNA has an interaction energy Vi. Vi is computed from the model for S. cerevisiae nucleosome positioning of Kaplan et al. (1), as described in the β€�Materials and Methodsβ€™ section. Finally, nucleosomes act as β€�hard coresβ€™; they are not permitted to overlap one another.We have three kinetic events in our model (Figure 1a): (i) histone octamer binding to DNA to form nucleosomes (nucleosome adsorption); (ii) histone octamer release (nucleosome desorption); and (iii) lateral displacement of histone octamers along the DNA (nucleosome sliding). The actual deposition and dissociation of nucleosomes involve multiple steps. First,  heterodimers are deposited by histone chaperones such as CAF1, and then  heterodimers are deposited by chaperones such as Nap1. During disassembly,  disassembles first, and only then the disassembly of  happens (24,25). However, for simplicity, in this article, we have approximated nucleosome binding and dissociation as single events where the octamer as a whole binds and dissociates at various locations along the DNA. Even though DNAβ€“histone interactions in the presence of thermal forces can, in principle, result in all the three events discussed earlier in the text, thermally driven nucleosome desorption and sliding are far too slow to contribute to nucleosome positioning in vivo (17). It is known that ATP-dependent enzymes accelerate these processes (26β€“28).
